h3 State custom behavior
p.-text
  | The three expansion panel states behave very similar one from each other. For example, you shouldn't, but you may
  | use an <code>m-epanel__footer</code> element in a <code>pending</code> panel, or an
  | <code>m-epanel__activator-header</code> button in an <code>active</code> panel.
p.-text
  | There are two main differences between them.
ol.-text
  li The title in the active panel will render in the brand color.
  li Two hiding utility classes will hide content depending on the state.

h4 Hidding by state
p.-text
  | The three examples below differ only on the state. Thanks to the state support and the <code>-active--only</code> and
  | <code>-done--only</code> utility classes, we can represent the three states of the same content changing only the
  | state class.
p.-text
  span.a-badge.-brand.-mr1
    span Tip
  | It is not a best practice to use this utility classes in frontend frameworks such as Angular, React or Vue as they
  | have their own solutions to accomplish this goal.

